<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GOSPEL ACCORDING TO MURRAY NOT FOUND IN THIS GOOD BOOKIE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gee, the pulpit's still warm. Jim Murray must have just left. 
</P>
<P>
Why not throw a few bucks Oregon's way? Because of some long-ago ignored edict? 
Do we, the people, bury our heads in the sand and wish away gambling? 
</P>
<P>
I have a cousin who happens to be a Catholic priest. Each year, he and I wager 
on who will finish higher in the standings, the Angels or Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
Is he a sinner now, morally inept? Does Father Murray proclaim himself more 
righteous than my cousin? 
</P>
<P>
My point is, gambling is a victim-less "crime." There are quite a few of us who 
are able to function every day and keep betting in its place. 
</P>
<P>
Why should Oregonians gamble and see their monetary losses driven out of the 
state to Nevada. This way, it all stays home and the losses help the state 
colleges. 
</P>
<P>
I excuse the vicar of The Times for calling me a low life. 
</P>
<P>
GREG MURPHY 
</P>
<P>
Pacoima 
