<HEADLINE>
<P>
'PHILOSOPHICAL BAGGAGE' OF EVOLUTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I read with interest your July 19 story on how the "battle over the teaching of 
evolution" is heating up again. I spend some time on that issue in my course in 
science and modern culture at Cal State Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
Ever since Darwin, the creation-evolution issue has been like an underground 
fire that erupts every so often. Could the problem really be that people are 
trying to resolve things by arguing them out within the arena of science 
itself? 
</P>
<P>
When you dig down to the roots, don't you find the philosophical issue of 
whether or not a God somehow superintended whatever processes brought life into 
existence on this planet? What if I won the California lottery, or had an 
amazing recovery from some catastrophic illness, and then asked science to tell 
me whether or not divine providence was involved? Do you really think it could? 
</P>
<P>
The problem with evolution is that, at least in the minds of a great many 
people, it seems to carry so much philosophical baggage along with it. If the 
word "evolution" is taken to embrace a satisfying explanation for the existence 
of all life on this planet, then the philosophical implications are absolutely 
enormous! 
</P>
<P>
I sometimes fantasize of a time when we could simply just stop using the word 
evolution in scientific contexts. We could create other terms with more 
precisely defined scientific meanings. The reason this is unacceptable to so 
many scientists is that they like the philosophical baggage carried by the term 
evolution. Why not find a way to teach just science in the K-12 science 
classroom and leave the philosophical baggage out! 
</P>
<P>
MARK C. BIEDEBACH 
</P>
<P>
Seal Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
