<HEADLINE>
<P>
'PHILOSOPHICAL BAGGAGE' OF EVOLUTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Times' editorial "Evolution Only, Please" (July 21) failed to comprehend 
the educational, scholastic and political issues at hand in Sacramento. Forced 
teaching of creation is not the issue. The Times used a non-issue as a smoke 
screen to twist public opinion and cover up the real issues. 
</P>
<P>
The issues are: 
</P>
<P>
1) The proposed science framework states that evolution is a fact and places 
this as a foundation for the entire work. The state Board of Education twice 
asked for its removal but framework authors have refused to make the changes 
the board has the authority to require. 
</P>
<P>
2) The theory of evolution is presented in a dogmatic way, without applying the 
scientific standards of testing, verifying, modifying and refuting. It thus is 
presented as a "compelling belief," putting it in the category of de facto 
religion, even if it is the religion of secular humanism. 
</P>
<P>
Additionally, material should be included in the textbooks that gives students 
information by various credible scientists. Yes, there are scientists who do 
not accept evolution (Michael Denton, a renowned Australian biologist, is one), 
who say that evolution, particularly macro-evolution, cannot be substantiated. 
</P>
<P>
3) In addition, this commission is suppressing the First Amendment rights of 
students and teachers. The Supreme Court in Edwards vs. Aguillard ruled that 
teachers have always had the right under the Constitution to discuss creation 
in their classes. Honig and this commission are trying to remove these rights. 
</P>
<P>
REV. LOUIS P. SHELDON 
</P>
<P>
Chairman, Traditional Values Coalition 
</P>
<P>
Anaheim 
</P>
</TEXT>
