<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: FORMER AZTEC QUARTERBACK BARRICK WILL PLAY FOR 
PALOMAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scott Barrick, who quit the San Diego State University football team before 
spring practice in April, will play for Palomar College this fall. 
</P>
<P>
Barrick, a 1987 Fallbrook High School graduate, said he was contacted Wednesday 
evening by Palomar Coach Tom Craft. The two met Thursday, and Barrick will be 
on the field when Palomar begins practice Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been working out with friends who I played high school football with, but 
I was working out with no purpose other than to keep in shape," Barrick said. 
"They were all getting ready for the season, and I missed that." 
</P>
<P>
Barrick, 6-feet-3, 205-pounds, started SDSU's final four games last fall as a 
redshirt freshman. He said he will continue to attend classes at SDSU and take 
enough hours at Palomar to keep him eligible to play football. 
</P>
<P>
Haywood Mathis and Paul Victoria, two freshman linebackers who were redshirted 
last season, will not return to San Diego State University this fall because of 
academic difficulties, according to John Rosenthal, SDSU sports information 
director. 
</P>
<P>
Mathis will enroll at Grossmont College. 
</P>
<P>
BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
The Primetime 3-on-3 USA basketball tour will be held Aug. 5 and 6 outside of 
the San Diego County Administrative building on the Embarcadero. The cost is 
$60 per four-person team, $50 if all four players are under 16. Each 
participant will receive a ticket to the Seagram's Coolers All-Star Basketball 
game Aug. 8 at the San Diego Sports Arena. In addition to the 3-on-3 
tournament, players will be able to participate in a slam-dunk contest, a free 
throw contest and a three-point shot competition. For information call 
1-800-888-DUNK. 
</P>
<P>
SOFTBALL 
</P>
<P>
Lucy Casarez of Bonita had RBI singles in the third and fifth innings as the 
West defeated the North, 5-0, to win the bronze medal in the U.S. Olympic 
Festival women's fast-pitch softball competition at Oklahoma City. The game was 
played before a sellout crowd of more than 2,000 at ASA Hall of Fame Stadium. 
</P>
