<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
TOP-SEEDED MAYOTTE ADVANCES TO SEMIFINALS AGAINST WITSKEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Top-seeded Tim Mayotte surrendered only nine points on his serve Friday in a 
6-3, 6-3 victory over Australian Simon Youl to gain the semifinals of the 
Sovran Bank tennis tournament in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
Mayotte, ranked No. 11 in the world, won five of his nine service games at love 
in disposing of Youl in 74 minutes. He will next face Todd Witsken, a 4-6, 7-6 
(7-4), 6-3 winner over Jim Grabb. 
</P>
<P>
In the other semifinal, Richey Renebert will play Brad Gilbert. Renebert 
advanced with an easy 6-1, 6-1 victory over Ramesh Krishnam, while Gilbert 
struggled to a 6-7 (7-5), 6-4, 6-4 win over Paul Chamberlin. 
</P>
<P>
Mayotte, who has not lost a set in three matches this week, had little 
difficulty against Youl, ranked No. 205. Mayotte, seeking his first tournament 
title of the year, did not allow a point on his serve until he had built a 5-2 
lead in the first set. Youl used his only break of the match to pull within 5-3 
but gave the game right back when he double-faulted on set point. 
</P>
<P>
"Considering I was slow to break in the other matches, I made a point of 
getting out to a quick start today," Mayotte said. "Anything can happen in the 
tiebreaker." 
</P>
<P>
In Schenectady, N.Y., second-seeded Halle Cioffi rallied to defeat Sandra 
Birch, 4-6, 6-1, 6-3, in the quarterfinals of the $200,000 OTB International 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
In today's semifinals, Cioffi will play Marianne Werdel, who advanced with a 
6-4, 6-1 victory over Stacy Martin. 
</P>
<P>
Top-seeded Gretchen Magers won her quarterfinal match over Ann Henricksson, 
6-4, 6-3. Magers will play eighth-seeded Laura Gildemeister of Peru, who 
defeated Renata Baranski of Poland, 6-4, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072989-0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 88301 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 29, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part 3; Page 7; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
117 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chris Washburn played basketball games at North Carolina State while high on 
cocaine and once used a friend's urine sample to pass a drug test at the 
school, according to a new book, "Personal Fouls." 
</P>
<P>
"Wash would play games on coke," a teammate is quoted as saying. "The first 
half, he'd play great, and then the coke would wear off, and in the second half 
he wouldn't do a thing." 
</P>
<P>
The book, written by Peter Golenbock, also claims that N.C. State Coach Jim 
Valvano allowed Washburn to play even though he was flunking most of his 
courses. 
</P>
<P>
Washburn left the school after his sophomore year to turn pro. Last month, he 
was banned from the National Basketball Assn. for repeated drug violations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BASKETBALL PLAYERS; WASHBURN, CHRIS; DRUG ABUSE; NORTH CAROLINA STATE 
UNIVERSITY; VALVANO, JIM 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
